    "1656049353eec351e4": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "e3302b86-9b1f-4bc8-a310-47fd9d908cd9": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "1) Bring sleep-aiding items",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "165604935313dd40c2-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>While it may sound obvious, making yourself as comfortable as possible will work wonders when trying to get to sleep on a road trip or flight.<br\/>With this in mind, a little bit of forward planning could be a wise move.<br\/><\/p><p>Think about things such as:<br\/><\/p><p>While it may sound obvious, making yourself as comfortable as possible will work wonders when trying to get to sleep on a road trip or flight.<\/p><p>With this in mind, a little bit of forward planning could be a wise move.<\/p><p>Think about things such as:<\/p><p>° <strong>A light-blocking eye mask<\/strong><\/p><p>Light is also known to delay your sleep, so if you’re trying to get your head down, it’s a good idea to bring things with you that will block out light. A light-blocking eye mask is great, but if you find yourself without one, you should aim to dim the lights whenever possible in the vehicle you’re in. <\/p><p>° <strong>A travel pillow<\/strong> <\/p><p>Finding the best position to sleep on a plane is tough. Mainly because our bodies aren’t designed to sleep upright. <\/p><p>So think about investing in a travel pillow, or even bringing one from home. Making sure that your head and the natural S-curve of your spine are supported can improve comfort and reduce back pain on long journeys. <\/p><p>° <strong>Dressing for the occasion <\/strong><\/p><p>Making sure that you’re wearing comfortable clothes is great for sleep and also for general comfort. So wear loose-fitting clothing that you can move about in – and remember to take some extra layers in case it gets cold.<\/p><p>Take a blanket with you that you can get cozy under, along with some bed or flight socks to keep your feet warm. <\/p><p><br\/>A <a href=\"https:\/\/jphysiolanthropol.biomedcentral.com\/articles\/10.1186\/s40101-018-0172-z\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">study<\/span><\/a> in the Journal of Physiological Anthropology found that feet-warming socks led to 7.6% higher sleep efficiency.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "e3302b86-9b1f-4bc8-a310-47fd9d908cd9",
