    "f83afcd6-c6a3-4618-a09e-99b21f0cfbac": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "62752a16-c78e-4539-8697-2a35050f2ff3": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "5) Fuel your body",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "template--15759384150212__f83afcd6-c6a3-4618-a09e-99b21f0cfbac-1666963208df4396b8-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Give your body the resources it needs to be in the optimum state for sleep and general relaxation when traveling.<\/p><p>Here are some things you can try:<\/p><p><strong>Stay hydrated<\/strong><\/p><p>Water works wonders. Drink it before, during, and after your travel – it will help your body to remain resilient during travel and more optimized for sleep.<\/p><p><strong>Eat the right food<\/strong><\/p><p>Make sure that you’re eating foods that nourish you and avoid sugary foods that provide you with short-term energy but shortly after make you feel tired.<\/p><p><strong>Limit caffeine and alcohol<\/strong><\/p><p>Both can be a huge disruptor to sleep. It might seem like a great idea at the time, but the relief will be short and it will result in restless sleep.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "62752a16-c78e-4539-8697-2a35050f2ff3",
